occurrenceRemarks: A group of manatees were seen in Safety Harbor, Florida. They were seen fairly close to shore, near a pier. They were swimming close to the surface of the warm water. They were in the Tampa Bay, which contains salt water. It seemed to be 4-5 manatees, including a baby manatee. The full grown manatees seemed to be around 7-8ft long. The baby manatee seemed to be around 3-4ft long. The manatees were light-dark grey in color. Some of the manatees had visible scars/past injuries, perhaps from boat propellers. Manatees are deuterostomes, and are specifically part of the Chordata phylum ( https://www.livescience.com/27405-manatees.html). A defining characteristic of Chordates are post-anal tail, which can be seen within the photographs of the manatees (https://ucmp.berkeley.edu/chordata/chordata.html). Manatees are usually found in warm waters, such as Florida, South Carolina, and Georgia. They migrate towards the South during winter months, making Florida a popular migrating site for manatees (https://www.fws.gov/refuge/Crystal_River/wildlife_and_habitat/Florida_Manatee.html).

occurrenceRemarks: This manatee was spotted on the Alafia river around 11:45am (3.29.2020). It was the largest manatee I've ever seen, coming in around 10-12 feet. I was shocked by its size, the pictures don't do it justice! It was longer than the kayaks that my family was using. There is a picture included that shows this comparison. This manatee was alone and it had many scars on its back (most likely from a boat). Manatees migrate to Florida's warm waters during winter, according to "https://www.savethemanatee.org/manatees/migration/". They can survive in fresh, brackish, and salt water as these are all types of water they encounter upon migration. According to "https://www.livescience.com/53164-animal-sex-manatees.html", manatees have a specific mating ritual. The females secrete a scent that draws herds of male manatees towards them. For 2-4 weeks, they mate. Females often have many males that crowd around them so only the most aggressive succeed. Their reproductive structures are penis and vagina.

occurrenceRemarks: Florida Manatee, Trichrchus manatus latirostris, Phylum: Chordata Family: Trichechidae Genus: Trichechus Order: Sirenia The herd of Florida Manatee I found found was located at Weedon island power plant in St. Petersburg Florida. I found the manatee herd adjacent to a turtle grass flat with extensive mangrove shorelines. These “water cows” appeared grey, round and had a prominent tail and snout. The Manatees are predominately Herbivores as their favorite meal is sea lettuce. https://www.fws.gov/refuge/Crystal_River/wildlife_and_habitat/Florida_Manatee.html According to the Crystal River Habitat and Wildlife Center Manatees can weight up to 1,300 lbs and reach lengths over 4.0 meters. These animals inhabit shallow coastal waters throughout Florida, Alabama, Georgia, and other tropical climates.

occurrenceRemarks: I observed two manatees; one mother and her calf. The mother was approx 9 feet long. The calf was approx. 6 feet long. They had big, flat tails, and small flippers. The color of both manatees was gray. They were floating with very little movement right beneath the surface. After approx. one minute, the mother surfaced and made some noise while she was breathing. They didn’t notice us, and didn’t seem to care about the fish that was swimming around them.

occurrenceRemarks: GEOPRIVACY NOTE: All my observations are posted with “obscured” geoprivacy. occurrenceRemarks: This organism had a round body and a paddle like tail. It's skin was a grayish color and was estimated to be between 6-8 feet in length. Organism had small, deep set eyes, no external; ears, two nostrils on the top of it's snout that it used to inhale at the surface of the water and a flexible upper lip with bristle like hairs on it. It also possessed two flippers towards the anterior portion of its body, each with a set of fingernails. Based on the location and characteristics this organism can be identified as the Florida manatee sub-species of the West Indian manatee (Trichechus manatus latirostris). It was found in an aquatic habitat located at the effluent of the TECO power plant in Apollo Beach, FL, which is a known wintering ground for the sub-species. Weather was clear skies with minute cloud coverage and temperatures in the mid 50s Fahrenheit. This manatee sub-species can be found in the coastal areas extending from Texas to the Carolinas. This species belongs to the Kingdom Animalia, Phylum Chordata, Subphylum Vertebrata, Class Mammalia, Order Sirenia, Family Trichechidae. Reference: https://www.tampaelectric.com/company/mvc/

occurrenceRemarks: This photo was taken on September 22 at 10:56am at the Manatee Observation Deck at the National Wildlife Refuge in Titusville, Florida. The weather conditions were partly cloudy, 85 degrees, and humidity of 68%. The habitat was a canal water way that had very murky water. The manatee was seen swimming around in a small inlet area, thought to be eating because it kept swimming in circles and stayed there for a while. This animal is classified as the West Indian manatee because of its gray/brown color, large body, a snout, and a large flat round tail that takes the shape of a paddle, with no hind limbs only the paddle for swimming. Source: https://www.marinemammalscience.org/facts/trichechus-manatus/

occurrenceRemarks: Manatees! This photo is from Three Sisters Spring. Although the waterway around it has hard edges and is heavily developed with houses (check the Google satellite view), the springs are still wooded and there is a roped-off section where visitors should not intrude. (Again, if you look at the Google satellite view on my marker, you can actually see the buoys and manatee-shaped blobs congregating within the safe zone.) There are manatees in the channel, however, and we saw tens moving out away from the springs as the day heated up. There are posted rules of manatee interactions, all visitors are required to watch a FWS video before entering the area, and human-watchers in kayaks who remind folks of the rules. A few manatees have attached GPS tags with floats (you can see one of them in the third photo), attached by either USGS or the NGO, Sea to Shore Alliance. We were on a boat with Buddy Powell, founder of Sea to Shore, who also grew up just a few water blocks away. Right as I entered the water, a manatee swam toward me and it was an intense feeling. Seeing its eyes, the details of its skin. Although I later would see that this individual was not full-sized and I mentally knew that manatees aren't a danger to humans, it was also intimidating to share space with a wild animal of that girth. That respect of space isn't often broached by either me or wild animals. However amazing it is to see manatees underwater, it also made me a little anxious about the interaction. I put my hands up before it could bump into me (to which the kayaker watchman scolded me, "one hand! one hand!"--which is the rule) and the motion made the manatee turn away. Later, the same individual (I assume) snuffled my flippers as I stood flat-footed and I had to curl my toes in so it wouldn't graze my toenails. I kicked myself afterward for not finding an underwater case for my camera. Not only for the manatees, but also for the other wildlife of Three Sisters. You can snorkel up the flowing outlet to the springs, and there were beautiful bass, needle-shaped fish and others in the crystal clear water. In an experience that almost rivaled the manatees, I watched an anhinga from about 6 meters away above and underwater as it hunted and successfully caught fish in the overhanging tree roots. That was amazing! If you're going to Crystal River to naturalise in the water, please get an underwater camera!

When they weren't enjoying belly rubs (you would too if you were covered with algae) they were munching on the many plants in the water. Don't worry, we were in the water with these guys under the direct watch of a fish and wildlife officer. I didn't include the photo, but one of the individuals had a large healed gash on its tail presumably an injury from a boat prop.
